<head><title>For the Record -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>For The Record</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
25-September-1995

<P>

<P>
<LI><B>Bob Dole</B> hits first downdraft in nomination bid in Ames, Iowa, straw poll. 
<I>Newsweek</I> notes: ``Dole's campaign has stumbled whenever he's ventured beyond
 his familiar Senate lair,'' warns campaign ``may be only one misstep away 
 from the kind of shake-ups [Dole] has engineered in the past,'' although for
  moment campaign manager Scott Reed and deputy manager <B>Bill Lacy</B> are ``safe.'' . . .<B> Bob Novak</B> reports conservative Dole advisor
  <B> Don Devine</B> being pushed aside. . . . Campaign ignited mini-firestorm by returning $1,000 check from Log Cabin Republicans, a gay 
   group. Log Cabin executive director <B>Richard Tafel</B> says Dole campaign solicited money, then, post Ames, ``basically figured they 
   could write off the gays because they need the right wing.'' <I>San Francisco Chronicle</I> editorial headline: ``The Dole Way: If You're 
   Down, Kick a Gay.'' . . . A <B>Pete Wilson </B>aide suggests a new Iowa strategy for Bob Dole: replace Scott Reed with<B> Ralph
   Reed</B>. 
   New Southern strategy? Replace <B>Sheila Burke</B> with <B>Delta Burke</B>. . . . Dole drops 7 points, from 42 to 35 per cent, in Time/CNN poll.
    Undecided column picks up the slack, jumping to 25 per cent. Rest of field in single digits. . . . Pete Wilson announces
     presidential bid -- again -- hits illegal immigration, affirmative action in speech with Statue of Liberty as backdrop. 
     (<B>Mario Cuomo</B> suggests changing inscription to ``Let us send back your tired, your poor, your huddled masses.'') . . . 
     <B>Lamar Alexander</B> campaign runs New Hampshire radio ads highlighting Wilson's former support for tax increases, affirmative
      action, scores California governor as ``political chameleon.'' . . . Continuing buzz around possible independent candidacies.
      <I> The New Yorker's</I> <B>Hendrik Hertzberg</B>, noting <B>Ross Perot</B> won 19 per cent after he ``had spectacularly proved his unfitness,'' 
       asks: Could a <B>Colin Powell - Bill Bradley</B> ticket win? ``There is every reason to think so.'' . . . <I>Wall Street
       Journal</I> reports 
       Pentagon is ``immune to the hype'' surrounding Powell. Senior officers criticize ``Powell doctrine'' -- military interventions 
       should only be undertaken with overwhelming force -- as too risk-averse. . . . <B>George Will</B> on Powell: his views on the centrality 
       of racism and the unequal distribution of wealth ``are shared by millions of good citizens. They are called Democrats.'' . . . 
       In Dole - <B>Clinton</B> race Colin Powell comes in at 27 per cent, both Perot and Bradley at roughly 17. . . . Documentary ``Inside the Republican Revolution,'' produced by conservative Michael Pack and hosted by Donald Lambro of Washington Times, airs nationally on PBS on September 13.

<LI>Presence of New Jersey ex-Gov. <B>Tom Kean</B> (R.) in official delegation to Peking 
conference on women supposed to make U.S. representation ``bi-partisan.'' But 
rest of delegation consists of Clinton officials; non-government delegates include <B>Marilyn Monahan</B>, 
secretary-treasurer of National Education Association, and <B>Marie C. Wilson</B>, president of the Ms. Foundation for 
Women. . . . <I>Wall Street Journal's</I><B> Al Hunt</B> debunks conservative assault on draft agenda by noting word ``mother'' appears 
13 times. But Independent Women's Forum head <B>Barbara Ledeen</B> notes most of those references are disparaging. 
(IWF distributes buttons: ``Sex Is Better than Gender.'') . . . Chinese restricted demonstrations in connection with 
conference to a special area in school yard. Demonstrations ``should not slander or attack leaders of the host country,'' 
explained one official. . . . Delegate <B>Lynn Cutler</B> tells <I>Washington Post's</I><B> Judy Mann</B>, ``The more light that you put on these
 issues . . . the more you help drive home the point that there are inequities here that must be addressed.'' President Clinton 
 announces task force to implement plans arising from conference. . . . Government advice to Chinese police officers, hotel desk
  clerks, or others who might encounter naked woman protesting at Peking conference: Throw a white sheet or coat over her. Taxi 
  drivers urged not to pick up naked women in their cabs.

<LI>Subcomandante <B>Marcos</B>, Mexico's masked rebel-by-press-conference, is angling for a left-wing political party, leaning heavily on 
Liberationist Catholic support, especially Bishop <B>Samuel Ruiz</B> of San Cristobal de las Casas. But a ``referendum'' on future of his 
group turned out less than 3 per cent of eligible voters. . . . Mexican Pres. <B>Ernesto Zedillo de Leon</B> is trying, with $2-billion 
bailout, to head off a ``debtors' strike'' by 7.5 million credit-card holders, cutting interest rates by as much as 45 per cent 
in a 13-month restructuring period. . . . Tough-talking <B>Ryutaro Hashimoto</B>, MITI minister who faced down Clinton Administration trade 
negotiator <B>Mickey Kantor</B> on autos, heads for leadership of Liberal Democratic Party (Japan's largest party) and possibly the prime 
ministership. Foreign Minister <B>Yohei Kono</B>, chief spokesman for conservative reformers, withdrew, faced with certain defeat. . . . Recent
 deployment of new super-quiet nuclear-armed subs off U.S. East coast ``may have been intended as a reminder of Russia's residual 
 power,'' according to former Pentagon official <B>Robert J. Murray</B>; Russian sub force will be 15 per cent larger than American in 
 year 2000. . . . <B>Gen. Aleksandr Lebed</B>, former commander of 14th army in Moldova, will run for Russian Duma in December elections, 
 with polls showing him beating <B>Boris Yeltsin</B> 38 to 8 in subsequent presidential elections.

<LI><B>Elizabeth Taylor</B> and husband number seven <B>Larry Fortensky</B>, announcing separation, say: ``We both hope this is only 
temporary.''


