<head><title>For The Record -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<H2><CENTER>For The Record</CENTER></H2>
<HR>


<P>


31-July-1995



<P>

<LI>Are House Democrats in a self-destruct mode? First came resignations by Reps. <B>Billy Tauzin</B> (D., La.),<B> Mike Parker</B> (D., Miss.),<B> Jimmy Hayes </B>(D., La.), and <B>Greg Laughlin</B> (D., Tex.), from Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee after it issued document by House Whip <B>David Bonior</B> (D., Mich.) attacking their position on Clean Water Act. A week later, Laughlin and 18 other Texas officials formally switched to GOP. (Number of such switches since <B>Bill Clinton </B>took office: 105.) . . . <I>Time</I> magazine reports congressional Democrats say ``Clinton has all but abandoned them on central issues'' and that ``more defections are probably coming'' in House. ``My guess would be a half dozen more will probably make the change before the snows of next winter melt,'' says <B>Newt Gingrich's </B>press secretary, super-savvy <B>Tony Blankley</B>. . . . <I>Business Week</I> reports that GOP strategists looking toward '96 ``think they can pick up 20 more House seats to pad their current 232 to 202 edge.'' Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee Chairman <B>Martin Frost</B> (D., Tex.) admits ``as many as 50 Democratic seats remain in play.'' . . . All this has mood turning nasty in House Democratic caucus. Queried whether he will leave his party soon, Tauzin says: ``I haven't been in the party for years.'' . . . ``The Democratic what?'' asked Rep. <B>Charles Rangel </B>(D., N.Y.), when asked how Democratic leadership is doing. Rep.<B> Bill Richardson</B> (D., N.M.) turned reflective: ``I think that for the morale of our troops we need some victories.''
<P>
<LI>Clinton's latest political make-over proceeding quickly as one-time GOP consultant <B>Richard Morris</B> elbows more liberal White House aides out of the way and gets Prez to return to his old ``middle class'' themes. GOP pollster <B>Alex Castellanos</B> sees the logic here: ``They're trying to move from something Bill Clinton's not very good at, which is being President.'' . . . GOP staffers doing negative research for '96 race are filling quivers as frustrated Democrats pop off at Prez. ``He is driven by polls and not conviction,'' says <B>Jesse Jackson.</B> And Sen. <B>Ernest Hollings</B> (D., S.C.): ``He's one of the most inadequate Presidents we've ever had, but one of the best campaigners.'' Meanwhile, only 36 per cent of Arkansas voters now say they would vote to re-elect Bill Clinton. . . . On GOP presidential side, <I>Washington Post's</I> <B>Bob Woodward</B> told CNN talk-show host <B>Larry King</B> that former Tennessee Gov. <B>Lamar Alexander</B> ``has a very good campaign organization. I've spent lots of time on it. Don't write him off.'' And
<I>Forbes</I> magazine publisher <B>Steve Forbes</B>  -- pushed hard by some conservatives to get in race -- says he would run as pro-life candidate but will not make decision until September.
<P>
<LI>TV producer <B>Dick Wolfe</B>, who shoehorns politically correct sermonettes and plugs for agenda of super-rich Hollywood liberals into plots of NBC's <I>Law and Order</I>, says recent criticisms of TV sex and violence are just ``pigeon flutterrings'' that will have little effect. . . . <I>New York Times</I> columnist <B>Frank Rich</B> complains U.S. astronauts portrayed in movie <I>Apollo 13</I> appear as ``the embalmed heroes of nostalgia.'' But newly syndicated columnist (and NR alumna) <B>Maggie Gallagher</B> sees movie as a ``blast of cold, fresh, invigorating air, blowing away the alienation, the self-doubt, the chronic whining'' of cultural liberals like Rich.
<P>
<LI>English Tories who voted to keep PM <B>John Major</B> party leader in face of <B>Thatcher</B>ite challenge by <B>John Redwood</B> will eventually go down to electoral defeat, says London <I>Sun</I>: ``The turkeys voted for Christmas . . . they'll get a damned good stuffing.'' . . . Even retiring Foreign Secretary <B>Douglas Hurd</B> is now backing off idea of a federal Europe. . . . Setting off protests in France by overturning a 20-year-old law legalizing abortion, Judge <B>Thierry Denervoix de Bonnefond de Lavialle</B> has declared the fetus ``a future human being, already alive.'' . . . Attending dedication of huge new mosque in Rome, <B>Francesco Cardinal Colasuonno</B>, papal nuncio to Italy, called on Saudi Arabia to permit equal rights for resident Christians. . . . Israel police commissioner <B>Assaf Hefetz</B> says Russian mafia has invested $4 billion in Israel in last few years, and may have been responsible for contract killing there in May. . . . <I>Washington Times</I> reporter <B>Ben Barker</B> says that threat of trade sanctions proposed by Sen. <B>Jesse Helms</B> (R., N.C.) has forced Colombia to step up anti-drug efforts, including recent arrest of Cali cartel kingpin, <B>Gilberto Rodriguez Orejuela</B>. . . . With more than 2,000 lingerie shops (as against 1,460 grocery stores) in Buenos Aires, Argentinian women ``spend two or three times more on underwear than their counterparts worldwide,'' according to <I>New York Times</I> dispatch from <B>Calvin Sims</B>. . . . More Cold War codas. Classified ad in <I>New York Times</I> -- ``Russian Space Shuttle. Perfect orig. cond. All paperwork in order. Government clearance obtained'' -- was for real. Russian-born Riverdale businessman <B>Victor Rylkov</B> placed ad and says asking price is ``$5 to $10 million each'' for two unused shuttles from former USSR.
<P>
<LI>Tough Arizona sheriff <B>Joe Arpaio</B>, who has moved prison inmates to tents in the desert, is also revising their TV fare. Shows with sex and violence are out -- replaced by Lassie, Donald Duck, and Newt Gingrich's 10-part video
series,<I> Renewing American Civilization</I>. Biggest hit so far with convicts is <B>Disney</B>'s
<I>Old Yeller</I> because -- speculates Arpaio, a non-<B>Rousseau</B>ian -- ``that's where they killed the dog.''
<P>	 -- OCD

