<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I> for November 12, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Newt: Should He Stay or Should He Go?</b><br>
	


The hot controversy inside Washington today was sparked by Kate O'Beirne's column in the current issue of <I>National Review</I> suggesting that perhaps it might be in the best interests of the Speaker Gingrich to temporarily step down from his leadership post, and if he did so a good replacement would be Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde. The column made ABC News, the <I>Washington Post</I>, the newspaper <I>Roll Call</I>,  and prompted remarks by Rep. Steve Largent (Okla.) that it might indeed be advisable for Newt to take a hiatus. Feelings against Gingrich do seem to run high among Republican freshmen who feel they were led astray by Gingrich over the last two years (many of them were shot at with bullets with Newt's name on them in the just-completed campaign). Also, the feeling that Gingrich has become a liability runs high among GOP opinion-makers in Washington, but until now has gone unspoken. The Gingrich forces were so worried about the stir that they reportedly called Hyde's office to see if he was collecting 
votes to challenge Gingrich in next week's internal Republican leadership elections. Such a challenge won't be forthcoming from Hyde, or anyone else for that matter. If Gingrich is going to go, he would indeed have to step aside voluntarily. But the Speaker is still in a precarious position. Yesterday liberal Republican Rep. Chris Shay (Conn.) announced he won't vote for Gingrich for Speaker in Januarythe public, official voteif the ethics committee report on Gingrich has not yet been made public. It seems a sensible demandbut, then again, Gingrich allies suggest this will only give Democrats on the committee reason to stall. Whatever happens, it will be a much reduced Speaker Newt Gingrich come the start of the new Congress, and Republicans have to be willing to think about the possibility in a few months of there being no Speaker Gingrich at all. 

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
