<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I> for November 2, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>"California Pandering"</b><br>
The <I>New York Times</I>'s latest insult to the intelligence of its readers was Thursday's editorial denouncing California's Proposition 209, the initiative to ban racial and gender preferences in state contracting, employment and university admissions. <I>The Times</I> complains that Bob Dole, "who voted for the landmark Civil Rights Act of 1964, and a stream of race-conscious Federal laws since then, could now be heard complaining that all of these efforts, including many he had supported, had turned out to be a 'blind alley.' " We will eat an entire edition of the <I>Times</I> if Mr. Dole can be proved to have repudiated the Civil Rights Act of 1964. Notice also the slippery elision between that act and race-conscious laws that followed: some of the language, and the entire spirit, of Proposition 209 is borrowed from the 1964 act, which was a historic blow against "race consciousness." But it gets worse. The <I>Times</I> blasts Dole for having "tossed around code words like 'preferences' and 'quotas.' " Oh, so these things are figments of the right-wing imagination. (Have you noticed, by the way, that the word "liberal" increasingly appears in quote marks, as in "the 'liberal' Paul Wellstone," as if only a shameless partisan opponent would think to attach that label to moderates like the Senator from Minnesota?) Then we learn that "Proposition 209 is a retrograde measure that would deprive state authorities of what little leverage they have to promote true equality of opportunitya point President Clinton has grasped." These are the depths to which standards of argument have fallen at West 43rd St. Clinton is further congratulated for having "defused an angry national debate over affirmative action" with his " 'mend it, don't end it' policy." In fact, Clinton has done nothing to alter the practice of race and gender preferences, and his Justice Department has tried to extend them. "Mend it, don't end it" is a slogan, not a policy. But perhaps in the Clinton era, the <I>New York Times</I> can't tell the difference. 
<P>
<b>Affirmative Reaction</b><br>
The <I>New York Times</I> is on to something, though. The political battle over the California Civil Rights Initiative has featured a veritable avalanche of sleaze and misinformationall coming from its opponents. Take the new ad campaign against it. One ad features Candace Bergen saying, "If 209 passes, we could lose maternity benefits. . . . 209 will cut funding for rape crisis centers." In another, Bruce Springsteen exhorts the "working men and women" of California to vote against the proposition because it "will legalize discrimination against women and girls in jobs, in education, and in sports." Ellen De Generes's ad makes a bizarre link between the initiative and "the anti-choice boys" of "the religious right." A. Woodard appears in yet another ad quoting Gloria Steinem: "209 could wipe out maternity benefits." All these claims have something in common: they are lies, deliberate and utter fabrications. Bubble-headed Hollywood types may not know any better, but the people who write their lines surely do . The campaign to preserve race and gender preferences ought to be ashamed of itself. Here's hoping California voters won't be fooled. But if they are, it will not be proof that preferences are popular; it will be proof that they can only be sustained by a campaign of vicious demagoguery and simple lies. 

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
