<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 10, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



The notion of "charter schools" is alluring (see, e.g., the last <I>Public Interest</I>), the point being to save public education by encouraging school districts to pay for innovative and rigorous new schools that evade excessive bureaucracy. But then theory runs smack into reality. The Board of Education in Washington, D.C., approved an application by A. . "Mama" Anigbo to open an Afrocentric charter school featuring standard English as a "foreign language," no failing grades, students dressed in military camouflage fatigues, and a staff including a convicted armed robber (the security guard) and a principal ("Mama" Anigbo herself) charged with assaulting a court officer and a housing inspector. When Susan Ferrechio, a <I>Washington Times</I> reporter, showed up to a do a story on the school, a mob of eight or nine students and teachers, including "Mama" Anigbo, told her to "get your white a out of this school," then grabbed, kicked, and pushed her out. Miss Anigbo (250 lbs.) alleges that the Miss Ferrechio (110 lbs.) assaulted her first. When Miss Ferrechio came back with cops and a photographer, a still-larger melee ensued. Well, a charter school can't be better than the people who run it, who probably won't be any better than the school district that hires them. Conservative education-reformers, take note.
</blockquote>


