<DOCNO>WT07-B31-173</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA029-000317-B004-512</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://nationalreview.com:80/nationalreview/extra/010797x.html 204.71.237.85 19970114083810 text/html 3244
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 08:38:00 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 07-Jan-97 23:32:08 GMT
Content-length: 3059
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>


<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 7, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



 <LI>There is a trade dispute brewing with the European Community over its demand that imported U.S. food products show whether genetic engineering or recombinant-DNA techniques (rDNA) have been used to enhance the plant's resistance to predator organisms. It is rapidly becoming standard plant-breeding practice to use rDNA to accentuate plants' natural defense mechanisms against fungi, insects, and rodents. The same thing used to be done by watching the mutations of plants in plant-breeding farms and selecting those seedlings that had better protection. Advances in molecular biology now let plant breeders go directly to the plants' genetic material to find natural "pesticides" and implant them in new plant breeds.
<P>
	By relying on natural plant resistance, farmers need less synthetic chemical pesticide and fungicide to ensure that human beings, rather than a horde of little critters, get the crop. This was exactly what environmentalists advocated vociferously a couple of decades ago when it couldn't be done. Now that it is being done, they are against it. They raise the specter of Dr. Strangelove scientists misusing rDNA technology to develop strains of fruits and vegetables with subtle carcinogenic properties. Killer tomatoes.
<P>
Scientists around the world have repeatedly affirmed that rDNA is no more capable of changing the nature of plants than seed-selection techniques practiced since cultivation began millennia ago. But the eco-hysterics got the agricultural bureaucrats in Brussels to draft regulations for special labeling of rDNA use. Now protectionist farmers in Europe are using the lack of U.S. rDNA labeling to exclude U.S. produce.
<P>
And where is President Clinton's Environmental Protection Agency? On the side of eco-hysterics and protectionists, of course. It wants to bring genetic materials under its regulatory authority the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act (FIFRA) by arguing that genetic extracts from plant materials are "plant pesticides" under the law and that they should be regulated and labeled in the same manner. FIFRA was enacted before rDNA techniques were developed and had been used to regulate conventional chemical pesticides. The EPA's effort to weigh in on the side of the anti-rDNA forces was signaled by an inconspicuous notice in the Federal Register.

</blockquote>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
