<blockquote>



 <LI>

 


 Mr. Clinton, in a CSPAN interview, took this not unreasonable measure of "right-wing talk radio": "I think that when it goes from criticism to ridicule, and particularly when it is at variance from the facts, which is quite often, it is not serving the country well." As much could be said about Democratic campaign ads, but he isn't <I>that</I> reasonable.
<P>
 <LI>The Heritage Foundation has produced an impressive new volume, <I>Restoring American Leadership: A U.S. Foreign and Defense Policy Blueprint</I>. The Heritage team of experts, directed by Kim R. Holmes and Thomas G. Moore, surveys the fundamental problems of U.S. national strategy, in areas such as challenges (especially in Europe, the Far East, and the Middle East), defense policy, economic policy, and the tools of policy-making (the UN, intelligence, foreign aid, public diplomacy). It is a well-done critique, with wise prescriptionsa needed antidote to isolationist undercurrents that would leave the world a more dangerous place.


</blockquote>


