<HEAD>
<TITLE>Housing Article #2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<img border=0 width=350 height=50
SRC="../graphics/sifnlogo.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<HR SIZE=4>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 1 -->
<h1>Unscrupulous groups target lonely, dying</h1>
<P>By Joan McQueeney Mitric
<BR>Maturity News Service
<P>Anna Tucker was 83 and a frail resident of a nursing home in Phoenix 
when proselytizers began daily visits to her bedside.
<P>"My grandmother told me this woman was preaching at her without 
being invited, leaving literature she didn't want and asking her to redraw her will," 
said Rick Ross, now a professional counselor near Scottsdale, AZ.
<P>Ross intervened before his grandmother gave money away, and the 
home drafted guidelines to screen visitors.
<P>Nursing home administrators, chaplains, elder law attorneys, cult 
specialists and aging experts are urging facilities to establish such guidelines, warning 
that the ailing, lonely or dying are particularly vulnerable to unscrupulous 
visitors interested in their money.
<P>Experts stress that legitimate spiritual groups that counsel the elderly 
offer an immeasurable service to people grappling with the profound spiritual 
dilemmas surrounding death. But they agree that safeguards are needed in 
nursing facilities, veterans' hospitals or at the elders' own homes.
<P>Groups may read newspaper obituaries to find recent widows and then 
knock on their doors with a friendly offer to run errands. Others go to 
mainstream churches to seek our frail people with the idea of gaining their confidence.
<P>These groups "play on the loneliness and neglect an older person may 
be feeling," said Margaret Thaler Singer, a retired professor of clinical psychology 
at the University of California at Berkeley who has specialized in the study of cults.
<P>In extreme cases, Singer said, a group may try to separate an elder from 
her family, physically or psychologically.
<P>"They say things like, `Your daughter hasn't called for a month. She 
doesn't care about you. Why do you care what she thinks?' " Once under the influence of such a person, older people may sign away their homes or contribute large 
sums to religious groups, cults or impersonators, Singer said.
<P>Some nursing homes are familiar with the problem and have put 
safeguards in place.
<P>After seeing a few cases, the Rev. Daniel Kratz, a United Church of 
Christ minister who is director of chaplains for Manor Health Care Corp., helped set 
up visitor guidelines for 160-plus nursing homes the company owns. 
<P>Without clearance procedures, Kratz said "cultlike people can come in 
and put on a seemingly nice religious service for the residents. But their motive is 
to find out who has money and to cultivate that individual later by going to 
their private rooms."
<P>He said "a lonely older person is especially vulnerable as he 
approaches death and is thinking more and more about religious issues." But Kratz 
said residents have a "right to refuse to see anyone, just like they would at home."
<P>Wes Toepper, a Lutheran minister and director of pastoral care at the 
District of Columbia's 800-bed nursing facility, has seen "every kind of visitation 
from every kind of religious group. Some of the most abusive people would be 
ranting about hell-fire and damnation to people who had no interest in it."
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->

<P>Toepper, who said he "came close to forcibly removing the most 
insistent," believes he must "protect the rights of the nonreligious person just as 
vigorously as I serve those who do want religious visits," especially at a federal facility. 
"It's as much a privacy issue as a religious one," he said.
<P>Though not aware of anyone at his facility who was defrauded of 
money, Toepper was concerned enough to put in a security system to screen visitors. 
He said county homes and veterans' hospitals may be more easily misled by 
volunteer visitors. "They are desperate for help and have much less time to weed 
out the rotten apples," he said.
<P>Chaplain Janette Silva at Manor Health Care's facility in Wheaton, MD 
said she tries to do a background check on "any volunteers who want to visit, work 
or pray with the residents."
<P>Florida group counselor Carol Giambalvo said some groups go to nursing homes or hospitals to recruit old patients with the "express purpose of getting them to revamp their wills."
<P>As a member of a fringe group herself years ago, Giambalvo said, she 
and other members were often sent into nursing homes to befriend unsuspecting elderly. Arm-twisting for donations began after they had gotten a patient interested, she said.
<P>"We had a holiday project that sent members into hospitals and nursing homes with these little gifts," Giambalvo said. "The patients were extremely happy with the visits and the special attention. We sang Christmas carols and spread cheer. But our real goal was to get them to join."
<P>Professionals like Margaret Singer say the children of elderly people must reconnect with their parents if they want to protect them from seemingly friendly strangers with hidden agendas.
<P>"Start visiting," she urged. "Call them more than once a month. If you can't be there regularly, try to set up a network of trusted friends who can fill in and keep them safe."
<P>Rick Ross said family members should be particularly alert if older 
relatives seem to be withdrawing, lose weight or begin to sound illogical.
<P>"Check out their new associates or any new groups they've joined - from book clubs to Bible seminars to New Age health clubs - to make sure they are legitimate," Ross said.
<P>Singer said adult children often get the first tip-off that something is amiss when they do Mom or Dad's finances and realize big checks are going to a group that is not their parents' regular church or a recognizable charity.
<P>Singer suggests children ask their parents' regular synagogue or church if it can supply rides to services and to inquire about other activities geared to older audiences.
<P><I>(The features provided by Universal Press Syndicate are copyrighted 
material and all rights are reserved. You may not reproduce any of these features 
or distribute them electronically, in print or otherwise without written 
permission from Universal Press Syndicate, 4900 Main Street, Kansas City, MO 64112, 
(816) 932-6600.)</I>

