<!-- Generation of PM publication page 1 -->
<B><H1>Higher Social Security earnings cap is finally law</H1></B>
<P>By Mary Beth Franklin
<BR>Maturity News Service
<P>Beginning this year, nearly a million seniors who continue to work past 
the normal retirement age can earn more money without jeopardizing their 
Social Security benefits. That's because after years of debate, Congress finally passed a law that will significantly raise the Social Security earnings cap, a Depression-era 
incentive designed to drive older people out of the work force to free up jobs for the young.
<P>But times have changed since that law was enacted in 1935. Rather than 
a shortage of jobs, many business owners - particularly in the retail, restaurant 
and hospitality industries, are complaining about a shortage of skilled workers 
and have turned to hiring retirees.
<P>&quot;Raising the earnings test will increase the standard of living of the 
elderly and help the nation's economy,&quot; President Bill Clinton remarked as he signed 
the bill into law on March 29.
<P>Business owners lamented to a congressional panel last year that many 
of their best older employees have had to cut back on hours or quit halfway 
through the year to avoid onerous cuts in their Social Security benefits.
<P>And many Social Security beneficiaries complained that while they 
were willing to work to make ends meet, the earnings test creates a financial 
burden they cannot afford. An estimated 900,000 workers over 65 lose part or all of 
their Social Security benefits each year because of the earnings restrictions.
<P>Under the earnings cap, Social Security benefits are reduced when 
recipients earn over a certain amount each year. The new law gradually increases 
that ceiling over the next seven years until it reaches $30,000 by the year 2002 - 
more than double what it would have been under the old law. 
<P>This year, workers age 65 to 69 can earn up to $12,500 with no change 
in their Social Security benefit. That's about $1,000 more than in 1995.
<P>"That's cold, hard cash they have earned through honest, hard work," 
observed House sponsor Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-IL., following the bill 
signing ceremony. "These seniors need and deserve relief." Workers earning more 
than the new limit will continue to lose $1 in benefits for every $3 earned over 
the limit.
<P>The earnings limit will continue to rise, reaching $13,500 in 1997, 
$14,500 in 1998, $15,500 in 1999, $17,000 in 2000, $25,000 in 2001 and $30,000 in 2002.
<P>After 2002, the limit will continue to be adjusted annually to reflect 
average wage increase.
<P>Supporters of the earnings cap increase pointed out that only older 
Americans who work are penalized by the earnings test, since seniors with income 
from other sources can receive any amount without jeopardizing their Social 
Security benefits.
<P>"Older individuals who are not fortunate enough to have a private pension 
or much in the way of savings should be rewarded, not penalized for wanting to 
be self-sufficient," said Horace Deets, executive director of the American 
Association of Retired Persons (AARP).
<P>"Raising the earnings limit is good common sense because both 
employers and employees benefit," Deets said.&quot;Older Americans have the skills, expertise, and enthusiasm that 
employers value.&quot;
<P>The Social Security Administration estimates that 65 percent of those 
who will benefit the most from the higher earnings limits when they are fully 
effective in 2002 will be retirees with earnings of more than $48,000 a year.
<P>The new law does not change limits already imposed for workers age 
62 through 64, which are more restrictive than those for older workers. However, 
as in the past, those limits are also adjusted every year to reflect increases in wages.
<P>This year, Social Security recipients under 65 who earn more than 
$8,280 will lose $1 in benefits for every $2 they earn over the limit.
<P>Under both the old and new laws, there is no earnings cap for people 70 
or older, who can earn any amount of income from any source without any loss 
of Social Security benefits.
<P>Seniors who work while getting Social Security benefits still must pay 
Social Security taxes on anything they earn over $400 a year.
<P>Even if their benefits are reduced because of the earnings cap, they are 
still subject to the same tax, which can be as high as 15.3 percent of earnings for 
self-employed seniors. That's because the self-employed must pay both the 
employer and employee portions of the Social Security tax.
<P>Higher-income seniors also pay income tax on up to 85 percent of 
Social Security income.
<P>The Congressional Research Service has estimated that in certain 
cases, when all federal, state and local taxes and benefit losses are considered, the 
effect on seniors whose wages exceed the earnings cap can be equivalent to a 90 
percent marginal tax rate.
<P><I>(The features provided by United Press Syndicate are copyrighted 
material and all rights are reserved. You may not reproduce any of these features or 
distribute them electronically, in print or otherwise without written permission 
form Universal Press Syndicate, 4900 Main Street, Kansas City, MO 64112, (816) 
932-6600).</I>
<BR> 
