<!-- Generation of PM publication page 1 -->

<H1>CPI change could lower Social Security increases</H1>
<P>By Peter Vilbig
<BR>Maturity News Service
<P>For months, the debate on cutting the federal budget has focused mainly 
on Medicare and Medicaid. But a proposal to chop the Consumer Price Index, 
which measures inflation and helps determine cost-of-living increases for Social 
Security, could also have lasting effects on seniors well into the aging of the 
Baby Boom.
<P>The CPI is a measure, compiled by the government, of the costs of a 
wide variety of goods. In recent years, there has been a growing belief among 
economists that the rate overshoots actual inflation. The index exceeds the true 
cost-of-living increase by half of 1 percent to 2 percent, according to a 
Senate-appointed panel of economists whose report was released in September.
<P>Some on Capitol Hill, desperate to find the $894 billion Republicans 
insist must be cut to balance the budget by 2002, have turned to the idea of 
correcting the CPI as a way to avoid deep cuts in Medicare, Medicaid and other 
spending programs.
<P>Lowering the CPI by 1 percent would save about $281 billion in 
federal spending over seven years. That's nearly one-third of the total cuts needed 
to balance the budget under Republican plans. 
<P>The idea of revising the CPI is supported by Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan, D-NY, and by another group of 22 conservative House Democrats calling 
itself the Coalition and also known as the Blue Dog Democrats.
<P>In addition, a bipartisan proposal from the National Governor's 
Association, which represents both Democratic and Republican governors, has also 
urged correcting the CPI.
<P>Supporters of the concept point out that the average retiree would lose 
only $7 a month in the first year of the cut. And they argue that the overstatement 
in the CPI is costing billions in what amounts to a kind of bonus payment to 
millions of seniors.
<P>"We are at an impasse"; Moynihan said. "We need money. I think this is 
the only way we can get out of this."
<P>But opponents of the proposal - including most senior groups - oppose 
any cut remotely approaching the 1 percent level. They say the effects will 
compound over time, so that in the 10th year, the average retiree would be losing $107 
a month - equal to about 5 percent of income for a retired family with an income 
of $20,000.
<P>Some economists also question that present cost-of-living adjustments 
are too high. They argue that while the CPI may be inaccurate for some 
wage-earners, it probably is more accurate for many middle- and lower-income retirees and for poor workers - those most likely to be affected by cuts in inflation adjustments.
<P>One of the main reasons economists believe the CPI is overstated is 
that buyers today substitute less costly goods when prices rise for some other items.
<P>But, said Merton Bernstein, an economist and law professor at 
Washington University in St. Louis, "There's a real question whether the beneficiaries of 
the programs affected fit the CPI analysis. The poor don't have choices that the 
rest of us do."
<P>For example, Bernstein said, well-to-do people may be able to choose 
among a variety of supermarkets, but poor and elderly people often simply don't have 
the mobility to get around that well.
<P>"Many of them have to go to so-called convenience stores,&quot; he said. &quot;So 
they don't have the substitution effect."
<P>In addition, seniors often are unable to get to discount stores, which 
are "primarily a suburban institution," said Bernstein. "If you're stuck in the 
central cities, as an undue proportion of minority and elderly people are, you're out 
of luck."
<P>Proponents of a corrected CPI counter that elderly people don't face 
many costs that younger people must pay where inflation is a factor, such as 
transportation to and from work and clothing costs associated with work.
<P>But Bernstein points out that older people also have expenses that 
young people don't, such as higher medical bills.
<P>In the current budget-balancing effort, Bernstein says, seniors are 
being expected to absorb too many of the cuts in government spending.
<P>"It's amazing and appalling, at a time when people are talking about 
equal sacrifice, (that) the major so-called savings are in those programs that affect 
the poor and the elderly."
<P>The Blue Dog Democrats have advanced their own budget balancing 
proposal. Their plan would reduce the CPI by only one-half of 1 percent. 
<P>At least some adjustment to the CPI seems likely to emerge from 
budget negotiations. Clinton administration proposals have called for small reductions 
of a quarter of a percent or less.
<P>Regardless of what happens in the budget debate, the odds seem high 
that the debate over CPI-based cost-of-living increases will likely go on as the 
government continues to struggle in coming years with the challenge of 
balancing budgets.
<P>With 42 million recipients of various Social Security benefits, all of 
which are tied to yearly cost-of-living adjustments, a mathematical reality emerges.
<P>"You multiply even small amounts by 42 million and you've got big 
bucks," said Bernstein.
<P><I>(The features provided by Universal Press Syndicate are copyrighted 
material and all rights are reserved. You may not reproduce any of these features 
or distribute them electronically, in print or otherwise without written 
permission from Universal Press Syndicate, 4900 Main Street, Kansas City, MO 64112, 
(816) 932-6600.)</I>
<br>
<BR> 
