<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: The Oregon Tourism Research File</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>The Oregon Tourism Research File</H1>

<P>
The Tourism Commission's research file contains a variety of information
on the visitor industry, and is available for your use.  Reports
produced by regional tourism organizations include, for example,
a report on Columbia Gorge residents' attitudes toward visitors.
 There are studies on the Oregon Coast and many other parts of
Oregon, economic research reports that analyze the effect of tourism
on Oregon, and strategies for future development of the industry.
 Out-of-state reports and reports on international tourism are
also available.
<P>
Various studies produced by the Department of Transportation have
been completed and are in the Commission's research file, including
studies on scenic byways and transportation improvement.
<P>
The Tourism Commission pays membership dues to several visitor
industry organizations in order to receive up-to-date tourism
and travel information.  The Travel and Tourism Research Association,
for example, sends out quarterly reports about the visitor industry.
 Other reports on file include Travel Industry Indicators (produced
monthly), and the U.S. Travel Data Center's series of reports
dating back to 1984.  Of these, the <I>Discover America 2000 </I>report
focuses on the implications of America's changing demographics
and attitudes about tourism and there are many other titles in
the series, including  <I>Tourism and Environment</I>.  Another
report, <I>1995 Outlook for Travel and Tourism,</I> includes the
proceedings from the 20th Annual Travel Outlook Forum.
<P>
All of these reports are available for your use at the Tourism
Commission.  If you are interested in borrowing some of these
materials, please call Doris Nelson at 503-986-0003.
<P>
<P>
Source: Oregon Tourism Commission (October 1995)
<P>
File name: RESEARCH.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
