<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Resident Attitude Survey</H1>

<P>
This is a survey of voters in Oregon who live outside the Portland
Metro  area (A separate survey was conducted in the tri-county
area).  It was conducted by Moore Information, Incorporated, an
independent, public opinion research company located in Portland,
Oregon.
<H2>Summary</H2>

<P>
Nearly nine-in-ten voters believe the visitor industry plays an
important role in the economy of their part of Oregon.  Further,
almost eight-in-ten believe it is appropriate for local governments
to promote tourism and rougly six-in-ten are aware that spending
generated by visitors creates tax revenues.
<P>
Additional evidence that the visitor industry is perceived as
important to voters was seen in that more than seven-in-ten find
benefits in the influx of people who visit our state, and roughly
two-thirds agree that the visitor industry is an important source
of jobs and new money.  A majority perceive the visitor industry
as less harmful to the state's quality of life than other industries,
and at the same time, while the visitor industry is perceived
more stable than the forest products industry, voters are less
convinced that the industry is more stable than the high-tech
or agriculture industries.
<P>
Looking at perceptions of visitor behavior, more than six-in-ten
Oregonians expect to travel within the state this year, and most
of them plan to spend at least one night away from home.  Interestingly,
70% of voters believe many of the people who visit the state end
up moving here, and voters are more likely than not to view this
as negative.
<P>
Finally, less than one-in-five (16%) respondents work for a business
or company which provides services to visitors.  
<P>
A summary of the responses to the survey follows.
<H2>1. What is the most important industry to the economy:</H2>

<OL>
<LI>Timber  47%
<LI>Agriculture  18%
<LI>Tourism  15%
<LI>High Tech  10%
<LI>Fishing  7%
<LI>Manufacturing  3%
<LI>Construction  3%
<LI>Service  2%
<LI>Mills  2%
<LI>Small business  1%
<LI>Aluminum  1%
<LI>Retirement service/Centers  1%
<LI>Schools/Higher Education  1%
<LI>Government  1%
<LI>Large business  *
<LI>Railroad  *
<LI>Real estate  *
<LI>Prisons  *
<LI>Don't know  9%
</OL>

<P>

<P>
* less than one-half of one percent
<H2>2. How important do you think the visitor industry is economically
to your part of Oregon?</H2>

<OL>
<LI>Very important 54%
<LI>Somewhat important 34%
<LI>Don't know 2%
<LI>Not very important 7%
<LI>Not important at all 3%
</OL>

<H2>3. Do you think spending by visitors creates tax revenue for
local governments or not?</H2>

<OL>
<LI>Yes 63%
<LI>Don't know 12%
<LI>No/not 25%
</OL>

<P>

<H2>4. Do you think it is appropriate for local governments to
promote tourism in your area or not?</H2>

<OL>
<LI>Yes 79%
<LI>Don't know 7%
</OL>

<P>
3. No/not 14%<BR>

<H2>5. To the best of your knowledge, are most of the visitors
in your area from Oregon, or from other states?</H2>

<OL>
<LI>Oregon 23%
<LI>Don't know 19%
<LI>Other states 58%
</OL>

<H2>Do you agree or disagree with the following statements that
others have made about the visitor industry?</H2>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
                                                  AGREE                 DISAGREE     

                                              Strong  Some    Don't    Some   Strong  
                                                      what     Know    what           

Most jobs in the visitor industry are          46%     30%     10%      9%      5%    
