<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: Talking Points on Tourism: State</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Talking Points on Tourism: State</H1>

<P>
As Oregon's economy continues to diversify, tourism plays a vital
role in creating new job opportunities and strengthening local
and regional economies.
<P>
In 1993, nearly $3.4 billion was generated statewide from visitor
expenditures, an 8.2% increase over 1992 expenditures.  Preliminary
estimates for 1994 indicate that expenditures increased 5.6% between
1993 and 1994.  This confirms that the visitor industry is not
only a key economic force in Oregon, but a significant growth
industry as well.
<P>
In addition to direct impacts, employment and revenue in support
sectors such as business services, utilities, and personal services
are significant.
<P>
Oregon's visitor industry provides important entry-level jobs
as well as increasing opportunities in managerial and professional
positions.  It also provides important transferable skills and
employment for women and minorities entering the job market.
<P>
Interestingly, tourism employment has grown at a slower rate than
payroll and travel spending, which in part reflects rising average
wage rates in the industry.  As the Oregon visitor industry matures,
so do the quantity, and particularly, the quality of jobs.
<P>
Between 1987 and 1994, growth in the tourism industry in Oregon
has shown substantial increases, as indicated by the statistics
below, not adjusted for inflation (prepared by Dean Runyan Associates):
<P>
<B>Tourism Economic Impacts</B>
<P>
1987: $1.8 billion
<P>
1993: $3.4 billion
<P>
1994p*: $3.6 billion
<P>
 100% increase (1987-1994)
<P>
<B>Tourism Employment</B>
<P>
1987: 38,541 people
<P>
1993: 54,532 people
<P>
1994p*: 55,500 people
<P>
 44% increase (1987-1994)
<P>
<B>Tourism Payroll</B>
<P>
1987: $355,262,000
<P>
1993: $642,256,000
<P>
1994p*: $672,000,000
<P>
 89% increase (1987-1994)
<P>
<I>p*=preliminary</I>
<P>
<B>Average Tourism Industry Wage (estimated in 1993 dollars; based
on survey of tourism businesses, 1989)</B>
<P>
$12,537 (28.6 hours/week; $8.43/hour)
<P>
$20,172 (adjusted full-time equivalent,
<P>
 including tip income)
<P>
<B>Average Tourism Proprietor Family Income (estimated in 1993
dollars)</B>
<P>
$39,768 per year
<P>
<B>State Tax Receipts</B>
<P>
1987: $ 48,531,000
<P>
1993: $ 98,545,000
<P>
1994p*: $105,400,000
<P>
 117% increase (1987-1994)
<P>
<B>Statewide Room Tax Receipts</B>
<P>
1987-88 $20 million
<P>
1993-94 $37.8 million
<P>
 89% increase (1987-1994)
<P>
<B>Visitor Volume</B>
<P>
Total visitor volume, 1994: 25.5 million visits (estimate)
<P>
8.1 million out-of-state visitors (32%)
<P>
17.4 million in-state visits (68%)
<P>
Out-of-state visitors generated slightly more than half of all
visitor expenditures in 1994 ($1.9 billion), but comprised one-third
of all visits.
<P>
1987: 6 million out-of-state visitors
<P>
1994: 8.1 million out-of-state visitors (est.)
<P>
 35% increase
<P>
1993: International visitors
<P>
 398,500 Canadians (+0.3% increase
<P>
  over 1992)
<P>
 224,000 Overseas (+4.9% increase
<P>
  over 1992)
<H2>Why Tourism in Oregon?</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Compatible with Oregon's commitment to a high quality of life
and protection of the natural environment.
<LI>Positive return on investment:
<UL>
<LI>For every dollar the Tourism Commission invests in advertising,
$19-$20 in new visitor revenue is returned to the state.
<LI>For every dollar the Tourism Commission invests in the State
Welcome Centers, $41 in new visitor revenue is added to the state's
economy.
</UL>

<LI>Helps rural economies diversify; links rural and urban areas.
<LI>Encourages regional partnerships and private-public cooperative
ventures.
<LI>Provides entrepreneurial opportunities (nearly 75 percent
of Oregon's visitor-industry businesses have a &quot;working proprietor&quot;
whose average family income is $39,768 per year).
<LI>Showcases the state and often leads to other business developments.
<LI>Generates more than $3 billion per year for local, county,
and state governments and private-sector businesses.
<LI>As tourism grows, investments in facility developments improve
the quality of life for all Oregonians.  Since 1990, these major
new attractions have been added to our product inventory:
<UL>
<LI>Oregon Convention Center, Portland (Sept. 1990)
<LI>Oregon Coast Aquarium, Newport (May 1992)
<LI>Oregon Trail Interpretive Center, Baker City (May 1992)
<LI>New OMSI, Portland (October 1992)
<LI>Museum at Warm Springs (March 1993)
<LI>Pacific Northwest Museum of Natural History, Ashland (July
1994)
</UL>

</UL>

<P>
<BR>

<H2>The Outlook?</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Nationally, the tourism industry is predicted to grow at 4
percent annually through 1995-Oregon has grown at a higher rate
than this over the past seven years.
<LI>Special-interest travel (ecotourism, heritage tourism, adventure
tourism) will become more important-Oregon's outdoor activities,
diverse natural beauty and historic attractions will be sought
after.
<LI>Cost-effective, safe, family-oriented destinations will become
increasingly popular into the next century.
</UL>

<P>

<H2>The Challenges?</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Ensuring that new facility development includes long-term
marketing support and operations funding.
<LI>Training and preparing the visitor-industry workforce; creating
career ladders and advancement opportunities in the industry.
<LI>Seeking public-private partnerships to alleviate housing shortages
during peak seasons and in primary tourism destinations.
<LI>Maintaining local, state and regional visitor promotion budgets
during difficult fiscal situations, and forming partnerships to
fund tourism marketing and development projects.
<LI>&quot;Internationalizing&quot; Oregon to better serve and
welcome international visitors.
<LI>Seeking ways to expand off-season tourism and alleviate congestion
during peak seasons at primary locations.
<LI>Encouraging more &quot;packaging&quot; of the Oregon tourism
product, making it easier for consumers and the travel trade to
purchase Oregon travel packages.
</UL>

<P>
Source: Oregon Tourism Commission (March 1995)
<P>
