<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: Sample Speech Outline</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Sample Speech Outline</H1>

<P>
It's probably no surprise to many of you that tourism is growing
in Oregon-between 1987 and 1993, just six years:
<UL>
<LI>Overall economic impact has increased 89%, from $1.8 billion
to more than $3.4 billion annually.
<LI>Our growth rate between 1992 and 1993 was 8.2%.  This compares
with 1.5% for California and 2.4% for Washington.
<LI>Employment has grown from 38,500 people to 54,532-a 41% increase.
<LI>Payroll has increased 81%, from $355 million to $642 million
<LI>And local room tax receipts have risen 97%, from $20 million
in 1987-1988 to $39.4 million in 1992-93.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
This area is certainly no stranger to this growth.
<P>
In the past few years, Oregon has witnessed unprecedented growth
in new visitor facilities:
<UL>
<LI>The expansions at the High Desert Museum
<LI>Oregon Coast Aquarium
<LI>Oregon Trail Interpretive Center near Baker City
<LI>Museum at Warm Springs
<LI>New OMSI and Oregon Convention Center in Portland
<LI>The Pacific Northwest Museum of Natural History in Ashland
<LI>The End of the Trail Interpretive Center in Oregon City
<LI>The reopening of the Crater Lake Lodge
</UL>

<P>

<P>
...just to name the biggest.  However, many more smaller projects,
from marina improvements to historic building renovations, to
scenic driving tours to plain old better marketing, have resulted
in a far more developed, comprehensive, and sophisticated visitor
industry throughout Oregon.
<P>
In spite of this undeniable growth in visitor activity throughout
Oregon, tourism continues to be the &quot;Rodney Dangerfield&quot;
of Oregon's leading industries and &quot;gets no respect.&quot;
 As tourism professionals, we constantly hear:
<UL>
<LI>&quot;Tourism jobs are all low-paying.&quot;
<LI>&quot;Tourism is a seasonal industry.&quot;
<LI>&quot;Why market Oregon?  People will come here anyway.&quot;
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Well, I'm here to tell you that tourism is not only important,
it is a critical part of Oregon's future, just as it is for our
national economy.
<P>
Did you know that tourism is the top export industry in the United
States?  
<P>
The travel industry is just like any other company marketing a
product on the shelf-if we want to compete in the marketplace
we have to be aggressive, innovative, and pay attention to trends.
<P>
Source: Oregon Tourism Commission (October 1995)
<P>
