<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: Oregon's International Visitors</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Oregon's International Visitors</H1>

<P>
A number of international markets hold significant promise for
Oregon: Canada, Japan, Germany, and the United Kingdom in particular.
 Research has shown that while international visitors comprise
only nine percent of Oregon's out-of-state visitors (and five
percent of total visitors), international visitors represent a
growth market for Oregon.  In addition:
<UL>
<LI>The average foreign visitor stays longer (11 days in Oregon)
and spends more ($96 per day) than domestic out-of-state visitors
(7.5 days and $84 per day).
<LI>International visitors tend to be younger, have a college
degree (59%), and hold a white-collar job (78%).
<LI>International visitors are more likely to be visiting Oregon
for the first time (53%) than domestic out-of-state visitors (30%).
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The data contained here has been compiled from research conducted
for the U.S. Travel and Tourism Administration (USTTA) by CIC
Research, Inc., and from the Oregon Tourism Commission's visitor
profile, conducted by Davidson-Peterson Associates, Inc.  Complete
research reports and an international marketing plan are available
from the Commission (503-986-0000).
<P>
<B>Total International Visitors, 1994: 205,000</B>
<P>
(excludes Mexico and Canada)
<P>
<B> Europe: 91,020 (44.4%)</B>
<P>
  United Kingdom 26,650
<P>
  Germany 25,750
<P>
  France 11,480
<P>
  The Netherlands 10,250
<P>
<B> Far East: 80,975 (39.5%)</B>
<P>
  Japan 44,075
<P>
  Korea 18,245
<P>
  Taiwan 4,920
<P>
<B> Oceania: 14,760 (7.2%)</B>
<P>
 (Australia, New Zealand)
<P>
<B> South America: 7,585 (3.7%)</B>
<P>
<B> Middle East: 6,150 (3.0%)</B>
<P>
<B>  (Israel represents 2%)</B>
<P>
<B> Central America/Africa/Other: 3,485 (1.7%)</B>
<UL>
<LI>Oregon ranks 25th compared to all 50 states, Guam and Puerto
Rico when comparing international visitor volume, not including
Canadians.
<LI>Portland ranks 37th compared to more than 60 U.S. cities and
destinations, with approximately 134,000 international visitors,
not including Canadians.
<LI>Major gateway airports for international visitors to Oregon
include:  San Francisco (17.8%); Los Angeles (15.2%); Portland
(13.7%); New York (12.2%); Seattle (10%); Honolulu (5%); and Chicago
(5%).
<LI>International visitors enjoy Oregon's outdoors:
<UL>
<LI>57% visit public lands and parks
<LI>46% engage in outdoor activities (hiking-27%; camping-15%;
viewing wildlife-16%)
<LI>21% visit historic sites and museums
</UL>

</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>Total Canadian Visitors, 1994:  400,000</B>
<P>
Source: Oregon Tourism Commission (September 1995)
