<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: Oregon Visitor Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Oregon Visitor Profile</H1>

<H2>Who Are They?</H2>

<P>
The average out-of-state visitor is a middle-aged, married Caucasian
who is affluent, has high educational attainment, and holds a
white collar job.
<H2>Where Do They Come From?</H2>

<P>
The majority of the out-of-state visitors are from Western states,
mainly Oregon's neighboring states: Washington (23%), California
(22%), and Idaho (4%).  
<H2>What Are Their Trip Characteristics?</H2>

<H3>How do they plan their trip?</H3>

<P>
Among out-of-state visitors to Oregon, the most important source
of information used to plan a trip to the state is friends and
relatives.
<H3>What mode of transportation do they use?</H3>

<P>
The prevalent mode of transportation to Oregon by out-of-staters
seems to be the automobile.  Nearly two-thirds of out-of-state
visitors drive to Oregon (57% car and 6% RV).
<H3>With whom do they travel?</H3>

<P>
Nearly half of the out-of-state visitors have two people in their
travel party (46%).  About one-fifth travel alone (18%), and another
one-third have three people or more in their travel party (35%).
<H3>What regions do they visit?</H3>

<P>
The Portland Metropolitan Area seems to be the number one region
in which out-of-state visitors stay overnight.
<P>
Portland Metro Area 48%
<P>
Willamette Valley 18%
<P>
Southern 14%
<P>
Central Coast 13%
<P>
North Coast 12%
<P>
South Coast 9%
<P>
Central 8%
<P>
Eastern 7%
<P>
Mt. Hood/Columbia Gorge 7%
<H3>What is their trip purpose?</H3>

<P>
The great majority of out-of-state visitors are on a pleasure
trip (76%), especially in the summer (85%).
<H3>What do they do?</H3>

<P>
The preferred activities among out-of-state visitors seem to be
the tourist mainstays of eating and shopping-dining out (61%)
and shopping (56%), in small towns (38%) and in metropolitan areas
(30%).
<H3>How long do they stay?</H3>

<P>
The great majority of out-of-state visitors stay overnight in
Oregon (93%).
<H3>Where do they stay?</H3>

<P>
Out-of-state visitors stay predominantly at a hotel, motel, or
resort, with nearly half of the overnight visitors using that
type of accommodation (47%).  The second most common is the home
of friends or family (36%).
<H3>How much do they spend?</H3>

<P>
Out-of-state visitors spend an average of $84 per person per day.
 From that amount, one quarter is spent on lodging (26%), and
another quarter on food and beverages (25%).
<H3>How satisfied are they with their experience?</H3>

<P>
Nearly all out-of-state visitors say they are satisfied with their
trip to Oregon (95%).  A very small minority say they are neutral
(3%), and almost no one says he/she is not satisfied (less than
0.5%).
<P>
Source: Davidson-Peterson Associates, Inc. (April 1995)
<P>
