<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Research: Talking Points on Tourism: National</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Talking Points on Tourism: National</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Travel and tourism in the U.S. in 1994 generated an estimated
$416 billion in expenditures.
<LI>Travel and tourism in 1994 was once again the nation's leading
service export . . . generating $78 billion in expenditures from
international visitors . . . creating a $22 billion surplus as
international visitors spent more money here than Americans spent
abroad.
<LI>Travel and tourism is the nation's third largest retail industry,
behind automotive dealers and food stores.
<LI>The travel industry is the second largest in terms of employment
behind health services.
<LI>Travel and tourism means 6.2 million direct jobs . . . $102.9
billion in payroll.
<LI>Travel and tourism means $56 billion in tax revenue for federal,
state and local governments.
<LI>States allocated $399 million to tourism promotion for fiscal
year 1994-1995.
<LI>Americans took 1.13 billion person-trips (one person traveling
100 miles or more away from home) in 1994, up seven percent from
1993.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Source: Travel Industry Association of America, TIA Communications
Department (July 1995)
