<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Sample Press Release</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Sample Press Release</H1>

<P>
<B>YOUR LETTERHEAD</B>
<P>
News Release
<P>
<B>City, OR</B>
<P>
<B>Date</B> Contact:  <B>Your name</B>
<P>
<B> Your phone # with area code</B>
<P>
<B>Tourism Industry Launches Statewide Awareness Campaign</B>
<P>
Oregonians will soon be reminded of tourism's importance to the
nearly 60,000 Oregonians employed in the visitor industry.  The
goal of the Visitor Industry Awareness &quot;VIA&quot; Campaign
is to better educate people within Oregon's borders of tourism's
role in the economy and how it contributes to Oregonians' quality
of life.  Banners, bumper stickers and public service announcements
will blitz the state this spring, and organizers are hoping that
residents will take notice and learn about the $3.6 billion visitors
spend in Oregon each year.  
<P>
Tourism is one of Oregon's largest industries and the second largest
world-wide.  Yet funds for tourism marketing remain scarce, both
at the local and statewide levels.  
<P>
<B>Insert quote from local tourism industry authority regarding
funding sources, budget restrictions, number of visitors to the
community each year, and economic impact locally.</B>
<P>
At the statewide level, Oregon ranks 45th in comparison with other
states' tourism marketing budgets.
<P>
&quot;A lot of Oregonian's enjoy the state's world-class museums,
convention centers, quaint gift shops, state parks, restaurants,
ski areas and events offered throughout the state, but few realize
that many of these attractions couldn't survive if it weren't
for visitors coming into the state and supporting the facilities,&quot;
says Sue Pickell, president of the Travel Industry Council of
Oregon.  &quot;Our job is to let Oregonians know that many people
in non-traditional tourism roles, such as graphic designers, chefs,
bus drivers, utility workers and architects are indirectly employed
by the industry, and that for every dollar spent on marketing
to visitors, $20 is returned.&quot;
<P>
<B>Local quote regarding local VIA Campaign activities, hoteliers/restaurateurs
who are placing the VIA sticker on their window and pledging their
support, etc.***</B>
<P>
     
<P>
The Travel Industry Council of Oregon is a non-profit entity consisting
of associations and organizations that benefit from the visitor
industry.
<P>
###
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (December 1995)
<P>
File name: PRESSREL.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

