<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: What is Media Relations?</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>What is Media Relations?</H1>

<P>
Media relations consists of interacting with the media, seeking
publicity or responding to a journalist's needs.   A subset of
public relations, media relations entails engaging a journalist's
interest so that the journalist will write/produce a story that
will reach your customer.  Typically, coordinating media relations
is one of the most difficult activities, because of the need to
find a willing journalist and generate interest in the story before
it ever reaches the public.
<H2>What does it take to initiate and manage a media relations
campaign?</H2>

<P>
Such a campaign requires a belief in the story you're selling,
the ability to think quickly and provide many angles to the story,
creativity, honesty in telling your story, likeability and patience.
 As in the case of all marketing activities, do what you do well.
 Don't try to be someone you're not.  If the idea of meeting a
journalist in person to pitch a story frightens you  (although
after meeting a few journalists you'll find them to be human and
usually very nice people), then perhaps sending a press release
and following up with a call is a better way for you to work.
 If you don't have great color slides or photos, then don't enclose
them.  Again, do what you do well-and just do it!  
<P>
Good public relations professionals must truly believe in the
story (their product or service), or they will often be viewed
as a hired gun that is simply out to do a job.  Someone who believes
in the story has an infectious enthusiasm which definitely helps
to sell a story.  
<P>
Most public relations people are able to quickly bypass one story
angle when it is obviously not of interest to a particular journalist
and present another &quot;hook,&quot; or even a completely different
story.  They are also able to find a legitimate story in ideas,
products and events that are, on the surface, ordinary.  Media
relations is sales!  
<P>
Honesty is very important.  Don't bend the facts under pressure
or make up an answer to convey the image of being an expert. 
Credibility is what the journalist is looking for, so tell the
truth, give good leads and recommend quality visitor attractions.
<P>
Likeability is another key to success in your business.  While
it's critical that you be an expert in the area of your product
or service, you should not appear overly bold or directive (i.e.,
&quot;Of course, you must do this story!&quot;).  
<P>
Although approaching journalists can seem intimidating, don't
feel that you must have a slick presentation.  Honesty and a down-to-earth
nature can be a great asset, especially considering that most
journalists are inundated by material from large PR firms on a
 daily basis.  
<P>
Patience and persistence are also important, since the primary
goal of media relations is to create good, long-term working relationships
with journalists.  If a particular story doesn't work for a specific
journalist or media outlet, accept that fact and target other
media outlets.  Maintain a solid working relationship with all
contacts for future stories.  Also, keep in mind that magazines
may have a lead time of 18 months to two years.
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: PR.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

