<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: How to Organize an Event</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>How to Organize an Event</H1>

<H2>1. Mission</H2>

<P>
Why are you staging an event? What is your goal:  fundraising,
awareness building, generating attention, attracting visitors,
educating, building community pride?
<H2>2. Theme</H2>

<P>
What is the cohesive theme that pulls the event together?  Arts,
children, time of year, entertainment?  Local activity, such as
a rodeo or harvest, or national celebration, such as the Fourth
of July?  What makes your event unique from other events?
<H2>3. Committee</H2>

<P>
Successful events are multi-faceted.  Few can be staged by one
coordinator.  It takes a team to pull together the details and
community support necessary for an event.  Select chairpersons
based on experience, ability to follow through and connections.
<P>
Sub-committees cover such areas as:  finance, publicity/marketing,
food, security, permits/regulations, first aid, guest services,
clean-up.
<H2>4. Work Calendar </H2>

<P>
Before choosing your event date, do a little research.  There's
nothing more frustrating than discovering too late that your event
conflicts with a major festival, holiday or committee meeting.
 Once you've chosen a free date for your event, work backwards
from the date to assign completion times to each activity.  Then,
move those dates back another two weeks to allow the extra time
that will probably be needed for each task.
<P>
The work calendar should include marketing, budget updates, outreach
to event facilitators (printers, permitting agencies, advertising
agencies, stage/ light/sound/tent vendors, food/beverage coordinators,
fencing, security, entertainment) and committee meetings.
<H2>5.  Budget</H2>

<P>
Determine budget outline and accounting procedures. Target potential
sponsors.
<P>
The budget could consist of office rent, equipment rental, marketing
efforts (printing, advertising, postage, telephone), food, souvenirs,
support services, guest hospitality, permits, entertainment, restrooms,
signage, security services, staff, travel expenses, etc.
<H2>6. Marketing</H2>

<P>
Create a marketing plan based on funds available, target markets,
and event message.
<P>
Create public service announcements (PSAs), press releases and
advertisements.  Determine marketing mediums, incorporate sponsors
in materials and get the word out locally as well as regionally,
 statewide, and nationally.
<H2>7.  Permits</H2>

<P>
Check on event site availability, and obtain the necessary permits.
 Secure insurance, if necessary, and review vendor contracts and/or
booth space rules.
<H2>8.  Refine Program</H2>

<P>
Review steps 1-7 and refine event coordination as necessary.
<H2>9.  Mental Walk-Through </H2>

<P>
Walk through the event mentally, as if you were a visitor.  Where
are the lights, ticket-takers, parking areas and signage?  How
is traffic flow, how does weather affect the event, where are
sponsor banners and booths, where are restrooms and handicapped
access entrances?  What is the communications mechanism?  Review
 the site plan.
<H2>10. Engage Work Plan </H2>

<P>
Redefine work plan as time progresses, and take notes regularly
as reminders of calls to make.  Review site plans, work closely
with sponsors and update your marketing plan as needed.  Have
a response mechanism (1-800 number) to answer calls for information.
 Get in-state publications, plan clean-up/tear-down, host volunteer
thank-you activity, keep documentation of planning process for
following year, etc.
<H2>11. Stage Event</H2>

<P>
Use logistics work plan with chain of communication/control for
decisions.  It is helpful to have a resource guide for key committee
members with home phone numbers, entertainment line-up, maps,
etc.  Have a briefing prior to the event opening and a debriefing
following the event to note improvements for future years.
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: EVENT.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

